.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A40185F33FCA1FD664CC63B9A" blockId="15.[826,1442,656,1016]" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">
Within the 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940185F33FC10FD664B523B63" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[994,1078,748,769]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carlosii">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840185F33FC10FD664B523B63" box="[994,1078,748,769]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">carlosii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup, with larvae distinguished by having marginal bands incorporating the thorax, and lappets that are not incorporated into the marginal band, the early stages of 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940185F33FB23FCC34A103B3F" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[1233,1396,840,862]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="volcanorum">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840185F33FB23FCC34A103B3F" box="[1233,1396,840,862]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">C. volcanorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are readily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940185F33FB70FCED4B973B1E" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[1154,1267,871,892]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carlosii">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840185F33FB70FCED4B973B1E" box="[1154,1267,871,892]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">C. carlosii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the longer posterior breathing tube, which below the ridge is more than twice the length of the tube above the ridge, and the black pupal spiracles with openings almost at the base.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A40185F33FCC8FB9A4A123C01" blockId="15.[826,1442,1040,1123]" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840185F33FCC8FB9A4CF13C47" box="[826,917,1040,1061]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">Biology:</emphasis>
Adults were reared from larvae in water tanks of the cliff-face bromeliad, 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940185F33FB2BFBA44AC53C26" box="[1241,1441,1070,1092]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Tillandsia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="15" pageNumber="282" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="major">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840185F33FB2BFBA44AC53C26" box="[1241,1441,1070,1092]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">Tillandsia major</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940185F33FCB0FBC74C843C01" box="[834,992,1101,1123]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="15" pageNumber="282" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Bromeliaceae</taxonomicName>
), and are known only from 
<collectingCountry id="4BE861EA40185F33FAEDFBC74A173C01" box="[1311,1395,1101,1123]" name="Bolivia" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A40185F33FCC8FB194B4D3CCA" blockId="15.[826,1065,1171,1192]" box="[826,1065,1171,1192]" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840185F33FCC8FB194B4D3CCA" box="[826,1065,1171,1192]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">
Subgroup 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940185F33FC5CFB194B4D3CCA" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[942,1065,1171,1192]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="282" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elizabethae">elizabethae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A40185F2CFCC8FB304E9339D3" blockId="15.[826,1442,1210,1906]" lastBlockId="16.[142,758,196,433]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="283" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840185F33FCC8FB304BD53CAD" box="[826,1201,1210,1231]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">Diagnosis – larva and puparium:</emphasis>
Marginal band complete round both abdomen and thorax; marginal band of mesothorax and metathorax each comprising two pairs of lobes; marginal band of first abdominal segment with three pairs of lobes (
<figureCitation id="ABC43DFF40185F33FB4AFABE4A6C3D28" box="[1208,1288,1332,1354]" captionStart="Figures 75–81" captionStartId="30.[142,232,1731,1750]" captionTargetBox="[317,1247,203,1691]" captionTargetId="figure-154@30.[313,1253,195,1699]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="Figures 75–81. Third stage larvae of Copestylum. 75. Copestylum oscillans, whole larva, head to the right, ventral view, length = 11 mm. 76. Copestylum carlosii, whole larva, head to the right, ventral view, length = 10 mm. 77. Copestylum elizabethae, whole larva, head to the right, ventral view, length = 11 mm. 78. Copestylum carlosii, sucker from 4th abdominal segment, anterior end to the right, ventral view, width = 1 mm. 79. Copestylum oscillans, marginal lobe from 3rd abdominal segment, dorsal view, width = 0.35 mm. 80. Copestylum carlosii, marginal lobe from 3rd abdominal segment, dorsal view, width = 0.35 mm. 81. Copestylum elizabethae, marginal lobe from 3rd abdominal segment, dorsal view, width = 0.35 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5429870" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5429870/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">Fig. 77</figureCitation>
); lateral and apical margins of each lobe coated with dorsoventrally flattened setae pressed close together and each branching apically beween three and five times (
<figureCitation id="ABC43DFF40185F33FCB0FA254CF43DA7" box="[834,912,1455,1477]" captionStart="Figures 75–81" captionStartId="30.[142,232,1731,1750]" captionTargetBox="[317,1247,203,1691]" captionTargetId="figure-154@30.[313,1253,195,1699]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="Figures 75–81. Third stage larvae of Copestylum. 75. Copestylum oscillans, whole larva, head to the right, ventral view, length = 11 mm. 76. Copestylum carlosii, whole larva, head to the right, ventral view, length = 10 mm. 77. Copestylum elizabethae, whole larva, head to the right, ventral view, length = 11 mm. 78. Copestylum carlosii, sucker from 4th abdominal segment, anterior end to the right, ventral view, width = 1 mm. 79. Copestylum oscillans, marginal lobe from 3rd abdominal segment, dorsal view, width = 0.35 mm. 80. Copestylum carlosii, marginal lobe from 3rd abdominal segment, dorsal view, width = 0.35 mm. 81. Copestylum elizabethae, marginal lobe from 3rd abdominal segment, dorsal view, width = 0.35 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5429870" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5429870/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="282">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
); ventral surface of lobes smooth and shining, fine setae confined to lateral margins except on thorax; sensilla 7/8 not on a long projection, except on abdominal segment 7; anterior spiracles absent; dorsal vestiture on segments 1–7 consisting of domeshaped papillae lacking setae; ventral surface of anal segment smooth and shining, lacking papillae and setae; mesothoracic prolegs lacking crochets; rims of suckers coated in fine setae; lappet pair 1 not on a fleshy projection, reduced to sensillum and associated setae; posterior two pairs of lappets incorporated into the marginal band, as shown by the presence of apical sensilla in two of the three pairs of lobes on the anal segment, middle pair separating them lacking sensilla; posterior breathing tube orange; elongate such that transverse ridge at apex of tube (
<figureCitation id="ABC43DFF40075F2CFDB7FF4E4DC538B8" box="[581,673,196,218]" captionStart="Figures 99–110" captionStartId="38.[142,232,1732,1751]" captionTargetBox="[245,1318,198,1698]" captionTargetId="figure-140@38.[243,1320,196,1700]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="Figures 99–110. Early stages of Copestylum, respiratory structures. 99–102. Posterior breathing tubes of third stage larva, dorso-lateral view, apex to the left; tr, transverse ridge; scale line = 2 mm. 99. Copestylum emeralda; 100. Copestylum otongaensis; 101. Copestylum elizabethae; 102. Copestylum louisae. 103–106. Spiracular plates of posterior breathing tubes of third stage larva, dorsal view; so, spiracular openings; scale line = 0.6 mm. 103. C. emeralda; 104. C. otongaensis; 105. C. elizabethae; 106. C. louisae. 107–110. Pupal spiracles from puparia, posterior view; scale line = 1 mm. 107. C. emeralda; 108. C. otongaensis; 109. C. elizabethae; 110. C. louisae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5429878" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5429878/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Fig. 101</figureCitation>
); cylindrical in cross-section and parallel sided; lightly punctate above the transverse ridge; spiracular plates close together and oval in outline shape; spiracular plates inclined, and openings consisting of three pairs of dorsal, circular depressions (
<figureCitation id="ABC43DFF40075F2CFE3AFED44D413916" box="[456,549,350,372]" captionStart="Figures 99–110" captionStartId="38.[142,232,1732,1751]" captionTargetBox="[245,1318,198,1698]" captionTargetId="figure-140@38.[243,1320,196,1700]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="Figures 99–110. Early stages of Copestylum, respiratory structures. 99–102. Posterior breathing tubes of third stage larva, dorso-lateral view, apex to the left; tr, transverse ridge; scale line = 2 mm. 99. Copestylum emeralda; 100. Copestylum otongaensis; 101. Copestylum elizabethae; 102. Copestylum louisae. 103–106. Spiracular plates of posterior breathing tubes of third stage larva, dorsal view; so, spiracular openings; scale line = 0.6 mm. 103. C. emeralda; 104. C. otongaensis; 105. C. elizabethae; 106. C. louisae. 107–110. Pupal spiracles from puparia, posterior view; scale line = 1 mm. 107. C. emeralda; 108. C. otongaensis; 109. C. elizabethae; 110. C. louisae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5429878" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5429878/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Fig. 105</figureCitation>
); pupal spiracles either yellow or black, with openings clustered on the widened apical third (
<figureCitation id="ABC43DFF40075F2CFE79FE114E8E39D3" box="[395,490,411,433]" captionStart="Figures 99–110" captionStartId="38.[142,232,1732,1751]" captionTargetBox="[245,1318,198,1698]" captionTargetId="figure-140@38.[243,1320,196,1700]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="Figures 99–110. Early stages of Copestylum, respiratory structures. 99–102. Posterior breathing tubes of third stage larva, dorso-lateral view, apex to the left; tr, transverse ridge; scale line = 2 mm. 99. Copestylum emeralda; 100. Copestylum otongaensis; 101. Copestylum elizabethae; 102. Copestylum louisae. 103–106. Spiracular plates of posterior breathing tubes of third stage larva, dorsal view; so, spiracular openings; scale line = 0.6 mm. 103. C. emeralda; 104. C. otongaensis; 105. C. elizabethae; 106. C. louisae. 107–110. Pupal spiracles from puparia, posterior view; scale line = 1 mm. 107. C. emeralda; 108. C. otongaensis; 109. C. elizabethae; 110. C. louisae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5429878" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5429878/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Fig. 109</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A40075F2CFF7CFE404EB63A59" blockId="16.[142,758,457,571]" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFF7CFE404E3B39BC" box="[142,351,457,479]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Diagnosis – adult:</emphasis>
Male head with a group of eye facets slightly larger than elsewhere on the eyes; wings without well-defined brown maculae; abdominal tergites more black than yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A40075F2CFF7CFDDE4F9D3CF3" blockId="16.[142,758,595,1169]" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFF7CFDDE4E353A0B" box="[142,337,596,617]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
This subgroup of two species is readily distinguished by the marginal band, which is complete round the margin of the entire body and includes the posterior two pairs of lappets. A complete marginal band is shared by the 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940075F2CFE0FFD444D353A81" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[509,593,718,739]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carlosii">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFE0FFD444D353A81" box="[509,593,718,739]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">carlosii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup, but lappets are not included in that subgroup. Furthermore, the mesothorax and metathorax have two pairs of lobes (one each in the 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940075F2CFE48FCA04D6A3B5D" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[442,526,810,831]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carlosii">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFE48FCA04D6A3B5D" box="[442,526,810,831]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">carlosii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup), and the first abdominal segment has three pairs of lobes (two in the 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940075F2CFEE9FCED4E0B3B1E" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[283,367,871,892]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carlosii">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFEE9FCED4E0B3B1E" box="[283,367,871,892]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">carlosii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup). Additional characters include the marginal setae of the lobes, which branch into between three and five setae apically (two setae in the 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940075F2CFF49FC494E6B3BBA" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[187,271,963,984]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carlosii">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFF49FC494E6B3BBA" box="[187,271,963,984]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">carlosii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup), the ventral surface of the anal segment is smooth and shining, and lacks either setae or papillae (setae present in other tank subgroups), and anterior spiracles are absent. Species of the 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940075F2CFD35FB954F823C31" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="283" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elizabethae">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840075F2CFD35FB954F823C31" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">elizabethae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup are known from epiphytic bromeliads in tropical forests in 
<collectingCountry id="4BE861EA40075F2CFE3DFBD64D303C10" box="[463,596,1116,1138]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="4BE861EA40075F2CFD95FBD64DDD3C10" box="[615,697,1116,1138]" name="Mexico" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="4BE861EA40075F2CFF7CFBF14F923CF3" box="[142,246,1147,1169]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="16" pageNumber="283">Trinidad</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
